          "body": "The chapter's first miracle is hidden in plain sight. Claudius's expulsion of Jews from Rome (AD 49) was, by every human measure, a disaster for Aquila and Priscilla — uprooting them from their home, their trade base, their synagogue community. But it deposits them in Corinth precisely in time to host Paul, share his tentmaking trade, and become his lifelong partners. The same persecution that emptied Rome of Jewish believers seeded Corinth, Ephesus, and eventually (Romans 16) Rome again with trained Christian leadership. Luke does not moralize the point; he simply lets the timing speak. God works through the empire's hostility to position His servants where He needs them. The couple appears six times in the New Testament (Acts 18:2, 18, 26; Romans 16:3; 1 Corinthians 16:19; 2 Timothy 4:19), always together — the canonical portrait of a husband-wife ministry team."
