          "body": "Acts 18:9-10 is one of five recorded visions Paul receives in Acts (9:4-6; 16:9-10; 18:9-10; 22:17-21; 27:23-24). What is striking is the timing. The vision comes *after* Jewish opposition and blasphemy (1:6), *after* the strategic relocation to Justus's house (1:7), *after* the conversion of Crispus (1:8) — when the work is fragile, the threats are real, and Paul, by his own admission to the Corinthians later, was 'in fear.' The Lord's words are tightly packed: a negative command ('do not be afraid'), two positive commands ('keep speaking,' 'do not be silent'), a personal promise ('I am with you' — the language of Matthew 28:20 and Exodus 3:12), a protective guarantee ('no man will attack you to harm you'), and an electing pledge ('I have many people in this city'). The structure is the Old Testament call-formula updated for the Gentile mission. The Lord does not lift the discouragement by removing the difficulty; He lifts it by making His presence and purpose explicit."
